Title: Always: Your Way
Comment:
Carter! In season twelve I submitted 100% pop, and you gave me a total of 4 points across the whole season.

Message received! After some deep algorithming, I give you - My Vitriol. Named after an item from 1938 novel Brighton Rock, they're a British/Sri Lankan band who released one proper album in 2001 (from which this song comes) and who coined the genre "nu gaze" by mistake.

I went back in time to see them live to confirm they were good enough for you - and yep, they still hold (held?) up.

(Matt McInerny)

Hey champ,

I know you're into all that drone metal stuff. And well, I tried, but I just don't understand it, and I'm scared of getting you something you'll hate. Maybe I went the wrong way, but I think this song is good as fuck and super straight ahead rock. That main riff is what's really getting it this place right now. Title: Strange Things Happening Every Day
Comment:
Sister Rosetta Tharpe is the godmother of rock and roll. She did the electric guitar before it was widely popularized. No surprise that rock music owes a lot to a black woman/black people in general.
Clearly you can tell Elvis etc was deeply influenced by her but she’s not nearly as well known today. I really hope you check her out if you’re not already familiar

Title: Cochise

Title: Johnny B. Goode
Comment: There are many ways to approach this question, but ultimately you would never have rock music and all of its harder later subgenres at all without the early icons. This is the rockingest rock in its purest, most authentic original form. No dilution or whitewashing. Even the Spotify bio says “Chuck Berry remains the epitome of rock & roll,” so case closed.

Title: Baba O'Riley
Comment:
This was tough, so of course, I considered a lot of songs. 

"I Believe in a Thing Called Love" was a bit too tongue-in-cheek; "Ace of Spades" so rocking but a tad  too metal. "Johnny B. Goode," "Whole Lotta Love," and "Layla" were all strong contenders. 

But 'Baba O'Riley' takes the crown. Iconic intro, great vocals, rocking guitars, from the peak era of rock. What put it over the top? What other song could get Joe Pera bouncing off the furniture?

https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=I79YNDYrUno

Title: Barracuda

Title: 100 Resolutions
Comment: To me, this song has a heavy theme of looking back on the countless past resolutions that you never really fulfilled. That's why this year I'm going to get ahead of it and just not make any resolutions! I can't fail!

Title: Fear The Future
Comment: I don't believe in new years resolutions because the concept of time terrifies me. I worry that by setting a resolution and putting an outward goal into the universe that I am somehow sealing my fate against myself and will end up jinxing myself in the process. The future is not certain and I will not be so audacious as to expect to have one which will allow resolutions to be sought, thank you very much.

Title: Absolute Lithops Effect

Of course, this is a lifelong thing. It gets worse and better and worse and better, but it's a long term thing. So I'm not really dreaming that I'm gonna make it all better this year, but I'm trying. I'll step outside, try and actually make some friends, maybe make some money. Get better again after a few years backsliding.

Title: Kokomo
Album: The Very Best Of The Beach Boys: Sounds Of Summer
Comment:
Growing up I watched a lot of TGIF (a comedy block on ABC compromised of two hours of family friendly sitcoms). I don’t know why, but every TGIF show had a “vacation” episode where they’d go to Hawaii, meet The Beach Boys, sing ‘Kokomo’ and foil a jewel heist. Every single show. Look it up. 

I haven’t had a vacation in four goddamn years and in 2024 I’m gonna take my wife to Hawaii and we are gonna have a proper TGIF vacation.

I thought Camilo was more of an abstract concept to describe how the singer is feeling, kind of a stand-in for needing help.

Nope. Camilo the Magician is a real ass magician that knows the band.

Title: Never Tear Us Apart
Comment: I heard this version of this song long before I heard the INXS original and when it used be on the radio I would always hear the words as "I was standing, You were there to work the lighting" and I had imagined up an entire story of the song being about a performer who fell in love with one of the stage hands who is infatuated by her singing (also always imagine this to take place in like a 1920s jazz bar) anyway of course it is still a beautiful love song, just not the one I thought it was

Title: Cocktails
Comment:
I was a kid when I heard this and only the chorus stuck with me. I thought he was saying “foxtails tore up my family,” not cocktails. So I thought it was referencing dogs accidentally sniffing foxtails, leading to their death. I thought there were family dogs dying left and right from lodged foxtails and this family was super torn up about it. 
Obviously the song is about the effect of alcoholism on a family, but you should still be wary of and protect your pets from foxtails

Title: Hexagram
Comment:
For years, I remember listening to lyrics like, "and the crowd goes wild. and the camera..." and "Worship, play," thinking it's about a young star worshiped by fans!

I never really listened further until recently, then I looked it up... Oh! It's about a suicide bomber.... okay.

Sidenote: This song may contain the greatest scream of all time.

Title: Clyde
Album: twilight as played by the twilight singers
Comment:
I love this song, but always found it maybe 7% too sleazy. So I was actually quite pleased to recently discover that, according to Greg Dulli* it's "a song about my cat [Clyde] and what a Mack Daddy he thinks he is". Having it from the perspective of a philandering feline now makes it only 1-2% too sleazy, I think.

* From The Afghan Whigs, the lowest voice of the three singers in this song.

Title: Excuses
Comment:
What I thought it was about: idk, just a nice slightly retro-sounding romantic but safe song that would be great to put on a mix CD for a then-coworker I had a crush on 

What it’s actually about: uh zero in on the line about “taping” the tongue to the “southern tip” of the body and go from there

Title: Speedy Marie

Title: Daniel
Comment: Thought this song was a love song for a dude a guy called Daniel when actually it's about the Karate Kid.

Title: Teddy Bear's Picnic
Artist(s): Henry Hall, The BBC Dance Orchestra
Comment: I always thought "Teddy Bear Picnic," was a straight forward song about “come-alive” stuffed bears meeting in the woods, but I recently learned about its deeper meaning. The song was written as an allegory for the Great Depression and it’s challenges. The woodland gathering represents shared adversity, the teddy bears themselves symbolize solace amid hardship, and the third person perspective is meant as a thinly veiled threat to American banks - stay out of our woods or the “bears” will attack.

Title: The Safety Dance - Short Version
Comment:
This isn’t a completely unserious joke, but more a mocking jab at authority. He wrote this in response to being kicked out of a club for pogo dancing to new wave music - which was framed as unsafe to the people disco dancing. 
While the meaning isn’t really hidden, there’s been a lot of confusion about what it’s about and the real backstory makes it so much better to me. I love that he was like “nah fuck this I have a fucking right to pogo dance” and then made this smash hit.

Title: I'm a Squash Man
Comment: https://youtu.be/fbC5YQ_oJoA?si=FuEm2a0KCx73LLSd

Title: The Wolf
Comment: Great song already, but the song itself is about addiction from the POV of the substance. Like if alcohol was singing to an alcoholic.

Title: Brighter!
Comment: I could talk about the meaning and brilliance of this song for 50,000+ characters and still don’t even completely understand it, but it’s very clever in that it has a simple, repetitive structure that’s almost intentionally like a nursery rhyme and yet it’s casually existentialist. “Brighter!” is a relentless call for light and heavenly type things that are also revealed to be terrible. Is there any true good or evil????

Title: Congratulations, John, on Joining Every Time I Die
Album: To Leave or Die in Long Island
Comment: A few months before this album was released, BtMI!'s bassist tried out for Every Time I Die against the wishes of the rest of the band. They notoriously played this at nearly every gig while the bassist had to cringe his way through.

Title: I Love Being Alive
Artist(s): World Peace, Beaver House First Nation
Comment: The joke is that the guy singing this song is no longer alive (he died)

Title: I Will Always Love You
Comment: I was over-thinking this but this is the one song I am compelled to explain everytime. Lots of people assume it is a love song / break-up song especially from the Whitney version but Dolly wrote this song when she was leaving the Porter Wagoner Show as a way of saying goodbye and thank you to the man who gave her a platform at the beginnging of her career. Though they may have been slightly at ends by the end of their time together, she needed him to know she would always be grateful for him

Title: Make A Fist
Comment:
i like a song that does something unusual but wears it lightly rather than drawing attention to how clever it is. this song has a time signature of 5/4* (five beats to a bar) - not exactly avante-garde, but still not easy to make it into something as smooth and almost danceable as this, rather than being some herky-jerky look-at-me king crimson nonsense. 

* as confirmed by the band

Title: A2Z
Comment: I had a really hard time with this prompt so apologies if this skirts the line. Logic says the alphabet through this song in order. He mentions it to his son at the beginning, but listening to it a couple of times, it's super clever how he inserts the letters into different syllables of words and phrases. Second runner-up I was considering was his song "Nikki" from Under Pressure, but I feel like that one is more obvious.

I thought about using Get It Together to bolster the problematic part(Q-Tip is also not the worst, but, well, Georgie Porgie happened), but this song is just way better

Title: Immigrants & Hypocrites

They have a history of cultural appropriation. This song about a black man’s experience written by two white women (and making money off it) is questionable.

Title: Fools Gold - Remastered Edit
Comment:
I have a personal connection to the problematicness here. Stone Roses singer Ian Brown shops in the grocery store I work at - usually cordially, but one time got really shouty and aggressive with some of my colleagues (& it transpired he'd once done 2 months in jail for something similar-but-worse). He's also an outspoken anti-vaxxer. 

But anyway....this classic pre-dates it all

(Also, we didn't ban him from the shop and are now on pretty good terms, so I guess he's also "our problematic fav")

Title: Old Friends
Comment:
I'm leaning heavily into the "fav" part of the prompt. The singer was accused of coercing a member of the band's crew into a relationship. The singer ended up taking a year long hiatus and making amends with the accuser. In the end, the most problematic behavior was maybe the “therapist” that released all this info for personal gain.

It seems this has been the line for me. I’ve stopped listening to a lot of other problematic favs. I still love this band and still listen all the time.

Title: Trap Queen
Comment: I have such a soft spot for Fetty Wap and find him oddly adorable, always have. I really like his voice and have always found this song sweet and romantic in its own way. However, he was recently sentenced to 6 years in prison for Trafficking 100 kilograms (220 pounds) of cocaine, heroin, fentanyl, and crack cocaine across Long Island and New Jersey. Sooooo...

Title: What's Up Fatlip?
Comment: I loved this song when it came out, and the music video is brilliant (dir. Spike Jonze), but the song has some absolutely problematic lyrics. So this is my favorite song that I can never share with anyone, ever. Except for right now. And prolly never again, ever.

Title: Revenge
Comment: Jahseh was abusive, a criminal, and a general POS. Once he was murdered the ongoing charges against him for battery were dropped. He suffered from mental illnesses and drug issues most of his life. He really struggled and made life for those around him pretty hard but a lot of people also say his story is one of redemption and recovery. People say he was improving and being a better person before he was murdered. He's posthumously become a bit of a legend. His music is hauntingly good.

Title: Model Village

Can't stop starting fights with people online and being a lunatic but that's fine cos she made this classic

"Well, her clothes are blacker than the blackest cloth /

Title: Sweet Baby James - 2019 Remaster

In college, I’d always listen when I was homesick and missed my family. Also JT seems like a nice guy and politically ok (liberal in an old rich DNC-fundraising white guy way which is at least better than some). It’s cute how the boomer ladies still go crazy for him at his concerts

Title: Tournament Of Hearts
Comment:
What's more wholesome than a song about Curling?
It's the most wholesome sport, and using a bunch of curling terms as a metaphor for a relationship is the kind of dorky that this round needs.

Worth noting that the singer's wiki has no controversy section. It does have an 'other activities' that notes he's been an adjunct professor of the Creative Writing Program at UBC.

Finally, no one in the Weakerthans have ever been to prison for trafficking fentanyl. Not even the bass player.

Title: Shut Up and Dance
Comment: The night that I met my girlfriend we went to a gay bar with a group and she tells the story from her side of how I was super shy and completely oblivious to her hitting on me in any capacity and eventually she got me out on the dancefloor and basically cleared everyone around us so the 2 of us could just dance together. This song was in the charts at the time and played that night and everytime I hear it I re-live the night as the song sums up exactly how it went for me. 8 years and counting!
